educational_summary: A warm mini-Neptune with a ~39.8-day year around a cool star. Its low eccentricity and moderate equilibrium temperature make it a good example of temperate sub-Neptunes.
A cool sub-Neptune with a long period (~226 days) illustrating survey biases and why long-period planets are undercounted in transit datasets.
A larger sub-Neptune with regular transits exemplifying Kepler's ability to find periodic dimmings from distant worlds.
A sub-Neptune with an ~11.72-day year that contributes to statistical understanding of close-in mid-size worlds.
A larger sub-Neptune illustrating how mid-size planets can reside farther out yet still complete quick years.
A very small hot world demonstrating high-precision photometry and raising questions about atmospheric erosion.
A warm super-Earth highlighting how planetary sizes between Earth and Neptune dominate exoplanet catalogs.
A classic hot Jupiter used to illustrate atmospheric inflation albedo questions and migration theories.
A sub-Neptune representing common intermediate-size planets largely missing from our Solar System.
A giant planet showcasing the diversity of close-in gas-rich planets Kepler uncovered.
Among the earliest Kepler-confirmed giants demonstrating how massive close-in planets produce deep regular transits.
A small likely rocky planet representative of attractive targets for follow-up characterization.
A hot super-Earth exemplifying very short-period rocky/mini-Neptune-size worlds and tidal locking.
A warm sub-Neptune with an evolved host supporting discussions on stellar radius growth and irradiation changes.
A warm mini-Neptune sitting near the radius valley prompting lessons on photoevaporation and mass loss.
A hot close-in super-Earth showing how tightly packed some planetary systems can be.
A hot super-Earth highlighting how small red dwarfs can host multiple compact short-period planets.
A sub-Neptune exemplifying small planets tightly hugging dimmer stars ideal for transit observations.
A warm mini-Neptune showing how short-period planets can be common around Sun-like stars.
A sub-Neptune in a four-planet system useful for studying orbital spacing and system stability.
A hot super-Earth exemplifying small close-in rocky planets abundant in Kepler's catalog.
A sub-Neptune underscoring how multi-planet systems often host several close-in mid-size worlds.
A fast-orbiting super-Earth with an ultra-short year suggesting tidal locking and intense stellar irradiation.
An ultra-short-period super-Earth with extreme proximity making it intensely irradiated.
A mini-Neptune typifying the populous family of warm Neptunes that Kepler revealed.
A sub-Neptune part of the large Kepler population ideal for statistical studies.
A small likely rocky planet illustrating how compact systems can host several close-in worlds.
A Neptune-size world useful for discussing catalog updates and evolving stellar parameters.
A sub-Neptune joining the dominant class of close-in mid-size planets absent from our Solar System.
A sub-Neptune in a compact system ideal for introducing TTVs and resonance chains.
